WEBVTT

00:07.682 --> 00:09.524
Last week we talked about this idea.

00:11.105 --> 00:14.068
Loved people, loved people.

00:15.550 --> 00:23.358
You see, if you know you've been deeply loved by God, then there's this natural or supernatural response that you can love other people.

00:23.378 --> 00:27.462
But if you don't know that you've been deeply loved by God, you know what this feels like?

00:28.363 --> 00:29.864
It feels like a book of rules.

00:31.346 --> 00:31.786
Do more.

00:31.826 --> 00:33.748
Do better.

00:34.789 --> 00:35.890
You're not doing enough.

00:36.450 --> 00:38.533
But I don't know if you know this or not, this is not a book of rules.

00:39.835 --> 00:40.717
This is a love story.

00:41.838 --> 00:51.013
A story of how God so loved the world that he gave is one and only son offering us forgiveness and redemption and healing and peace and so much more.

00:51.053 --> 00:58.564
We have been so deeply loved by Jesus that, well, if we recognize it and met him, it's gonna flow out of us to other people.

00:59.586 --> 01:03.352
And last weekend we talked about the identities that all of us had before he met Jesus.

01:03.592 --> 01:04.754
How many sinners in the house?

01:06.146 --> 01:09.050
Okay, so if you came here, you're like, oh, man, this is a place full of righteous people.

01:09.310 --> 01:11.833
Hey, not so much.

01:11.933 --> 01:14.116
Our identity as sinners, that's who we are.

01:14.176 --> 01:18.641
Then Jesus met us and the gospel tells us that even though we were sinners, Christ died for us.

01:18.661 --> 01:20.684
So we can't look down on anyone.

01:21.805 --> 01:29.775
Christians don't have the possible to look down on anyone because some of the greatest Christians were some of the darkest and deepest sinners, but God rescued us.

01:29.795 --> 01:32.338
So God has taken us from sinners, listen,

01:33.026 --> 01:33.607
to saint.

01:33.627 --> 01:35.530
Your primary identity is not a sinner.

01:35.570 --> 01:37.393
It's a sinner saved by grace or a saint.

01:37.413 --> 01:38.835
So if you're a saint and a house, raise your hand.

01:39.055 --> 01:43.723
If you've been saved by Jesus, if you are a Christian, you are a saint, a son or daughter of God.

01:44.744 --> 01:46.447
And so we live in this identity.

01:46.487 --> 01:49.692
We are sinners who are saved by grace.

01:49.732 --> 01:51.555
And now we're saints, we're sons and daughters.

01:51.595 --> 01:55.120
And one of the questions we ask is, well, how can we be like our father?

01:56.462 --> 02:01.330
Jesus is constantly asking us, you know, your father in heaven is kind.

02:02.146 --> 02:04.088
Your father in heaven is just and merciful.

02:04.128 --> 02:07.191
So be like your father in heaven.

02:07.291 --> 02:11.475
It's a relationship, not a rule book, but every once in a while.

02:12.476 --> 02:14.058
Well, Christians get lost.

02:14.118 --> 02:15.580
Followers of God, they get lost.

02:15.640 --> 02:20.765
And so that's when God sends prophets to speak, prophets to correct.

02:21.125 --> 02:27.011
And prophets say a word that sounds harsh, but it's a word that's hard, but it's a word that heals.

02:27.972 --> 02:29.874
And well, most Christians,

02:30.306 --> 02:34.012
We sort of avoid the prophets, but the prophets make up about one fifth of your Bible.

02:35.094 --> 02:42.185
Prophets like Isaiah and Jeremiah and Ezekiel and Daniel and prophets aren't just talking about the future, though they talk a lot about the future.

02:42.966 --> 02:47.353
Prophets have a way of truth telling, of speaking into a moment.

02:47.373 --> 02:51.219
You see, we're about to read a passage from the book of Isaiah.

02:52.101 --> 02:55.346
And like most of the prophets, the people are complaining to God.

02:55.906 --> 02:58.350
God, I don't like the way that you're running the world.

02:58.370 --> 02:59.071
Have you ever thought that?

02:59.111 --> 03:00.233
God, I don't like the way you're running the world.

03:00.253 --> 03:01.395
Just be honest.

03:01.415 --> 03:03.057
I don't like the way God runs the world some days.

03:03.999 --> 03:06.964
Am I the only person out here saying, God, I don't like the way you run the world?

03:08.506 --> 03:10.589
If I was God, I would do it a lot different, but I'm not God.

03:10.610 --> 03:11.831
Thank God, I'm not God, right?

03:13.735 --> 03:15.137
God, we don't like the way you're running the world.

03:15.958 --> 03:20.946
And the prophets are the place where God talks back.

03:21.698 --> 03:28.828
And if you wanna read any part of the Bible that really reveals God as a person, the prophets are the most revealing.

03:29.750 --> 03:35.097
This person who is God, who desires a relationship with his people.

03:35.638 --> 03:42.608
And he's gonna say to the people, hey, something is missing in your life, in your worship.

03:42.688 --> 03:44.110
It's Isaiah chapter 58.

03:44.210 --> 03:49.618
Isaiah is speaking for God, and here's what God says, verse two.

03:50.338 --> 03:52.440
For day after day, they seek me out.

03:53.121 --> 03:59.767
They seem eager to know my ways as if they were a nation that does what is right and is not forsaken the commands of its God.

04:00.428 --> 04:04.812
They ask me for just decisions and they seem eager for God to come near them.

04:06.293 --> 04:09.576
Now, why have we fasted, they say, and you have not seen it?

04:09.637 --> 04:11.819
Why have we humbled ourselves and you have not noticed?

04:12.960 --> 04:19.506
Yet on the day of your fasting, you do as you please and exploit all the workers.

04:20.194 --> 04:29.645
and your fasting ends in quarreling and strife, and in striking each other with wicked fists, you cannot fast as you do today and expect your voice to be heard on high.

04:30.606 --> 04:34.451
Is this the kind of fast I've chosen, only a day for people to humble themselves?

04:36.172 --> 04:40.297
Is it only for bowing one's head like a reed or a line in sackcloth and ashes?

04:40.598 --> 04:44.402
Is that what you call a fast, a day acceptable to the Lord?

04:45.058 --> 04:45.799
What's happening here?

04:45.859 --> 04:50.046
God is responding back to the people who are saying, God, why aren't you answering our prayer?

04:50.086 --> 04:50.967
Why aren't you with us?

04:51.728 --> 04:52.810
Why aren't you for us?

04:53.691 --> 04:55.114
And God's like, well, I got a question for you.

04:55.154 --> 04:58.299
You seem so eager to follow me.

04:59.340 --> 05:13.362
You gather together and you worship and you're fasting, but I can see past that facade because as you worship in fast, this hour a week, you come to worship, you sing your songs, you read my word,

05:13.666 --> 05:16.590
with hold food from your body to show honor.

05:18.332 --> 05:22.216
If you want to be honest, God says, I can see through that ritual, it's very empty.

05:23.097 --> 05:31.828
Because as you pray and worship for your hour a week and you fast, you're exploiting your employees and you're fighting and quarreling with your brothers.

05:32.549 --> 05:37.134
And God's like, you don't think I see through those empty rituals?

05:37.154 --> 05:40.038
How many of you that God cannot be tricked or fooled?

05:40.298 --> 05:42.040
God sees and knows all things.

05:42.060 --> 05:43.602
And so he's saying in a very,

05:43.906 --> 05:45.908
incisive way, a very direct way.

05:45.989 --> 05:47.911
I can see past this facade.

05:48.652 --> 05:52.376
And so then he shares what he's looking for in his people, verse six.

05:53.217 --> 06:03.971
He's not this the kind of fasting I have chosen to lose the chains of injustice and untie the cords of the yoke and set the oppressed free and break every yoke.

06:04.051 --> 06:08.296
Is it not to share your food with the hungry and to provide the poor wanderer with shelter?

06:08.316 --> 06:13.202
And will you see the naked to clothe them and not to turn away from your own flesh

06:13.666 --> 06:14.106
and blood.

06:15.448 --> 06:20.113
God says, if you want to worship in a way that's authentic and genuine, it's not just an hour a week.

06:20.893 --> 06:22.595
It's not just a song that you sing.

06:22.615 --> 06:27.080
No, it's the way you treat other people, especially people who are vulnerable.

06:27.941 --> 06:39.232
It could be someone who works for you, it's someone who's maybe a fatherless child or a single parent or someone who doesn't have the same advantage as a privilege as a view that we should turn our eyes toward them.

06:39.512 --> 06:41.234
And that's what worship looks like.

06:41.346 --> 06:47.856
And God's trying to reorient the people through the voice of the prophet Isaiah to say this simple idea.

06:48.196 --> 06:52.963
Vertical worship requires horizontal compassion.

06:53.845 --> 07:00.375
In other words, if the vertical doesn't line up with the horizontal, then something is missing.

07:01.677 --> 07:03.579
And so we want to be thoughtful as the people of God.

07:03.599 --> 07:07.065
Wait, when I come to church and I sing those songs, I sing them with my heart.

07:07.145 --> 07:10.610
I mean them and I open my Bible and I pray, but when I leave here,

07:11.170 --> 07:15.477
What happens to my life Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday?

07:15.517 --> 07:22.169
Because if it's only an hour a week and it doesn't affect my personal life, then my worship words and songs are empty.

07:22.189 --> 07:32.025
In fact, God will go further through the prophet Amos to say something that when you first hear it, you're like, wow, God sounds angry.

07:33.307 --> 07:35.090
Amos is a fig farmer.

07:35.691 --> 07:37.234
He's a poor shepherd.

07:37.506 --> 07:42.512
And God gives him a word about the songs of worship and the gathering of God's people.

07:42.752 --> 07:49.860
And this is what he says through the prophet Isaiah, or prophet Amos, Amos chapter five.

07:49.880 --> 07:53.765
I hate, I despise your religious festivals.

07:54.446 --> 07:56.448
Your assemblies are a stench to me.

07:57.729 --> 08:00.933
Even though you bring me burnt offerings and grain offerings, I will not accept them.

08:01.474 --> 08:05.138
Though you bring choice fellowship offerings, I will have no regard for them.

08:05.794 --> 08:07.877
away with the noise of your songs.

08:09.038 --> 08:20.532
I will not listen to the music of your harps, but let justice roll on like a river and righteousness like a never failing stream."

08:22.034 --> 08:23.355
Did you just read what I just read?

08:24.897 --> 08:25.859
God says, stop singing.

08:27.861 --> 08:29.022
Stop your joyful songs.

08:29.042 --> 08:31.986
Stop all your instruments because that vertical worship you're giving me.

08:33.186 --> 08:36.551
isn't translated at all in your everyday life.

08:37.172 --> 08:45.646
And if you want those songs to reach heaven and if you want my presence to inhabit you and you want to live the blessed life that I offer you, then those two things have to match.

08:46.768 --> 08:51.675
So stop your singing and go out and show justice and mercy.

08:51.695 --> 08:53.058
Let it roll like a river.

08:53.118 --> 08:57.465
Now what does it mean for justice and righteousness and mercy to roll like a river?

08:58.446 --> 09:00.850
It means that it spills out from God's people.

09:01.570 --> 09:08.560
and it flows into our communities, into our neighborhoods, all over, saturating people with the love and the justice and the righteousness of God.

09:08.620 --> 09:14.128
And the prophets were so curious, how is God gonna do that?

09:15.771 --> 09:25.845
Well, God's gonna do that through the coming of Messiah because the prophets didn't just look at the condition of God's people and say, they're lost, they're stumbling, they're broken, they can't find their way.

09:25.885 --> 09:29.010
So God doesn't say, well, it stinks to be you.

09:30.146 --> 09:32.428
Now this is when he sends his son, Jesus.

09:33.669 --> 09:38.534
And when Jesus comes into the world, he uses the very words of the prophet to introduce his mission.

09:39.575 --> 09:48.283
As Jesus goes into the synagogue to talk about why he has come and what his mission is, he uses Isaiah's own words.

09:48.323 --> 09:58.232
If you just turn just one page to Isaiah 61, Jesus first introduction to his hometown in the synagogue is this passage.

09:58.252 --> 10:00.114
Here's what Jesus says.

10:00.450 --> 10:02.553
about the coming of Messiah.

10:03.955 --> 10:11.526
Isaiah 61, verse one, the spirit of the sovereign Lord is on me, because the Lord has anointed me to proclaim good news to the poor.

10:12.487 --> 10:23.382
He has sent me to bind up the brokenhearted, to proclaim freedom for the captives, and the release from darkness for the prisoners, and to proclaim the year of the Lord's favor and the day of the vengeance of our God.

10:24.844 --> 10:29.010
Jesus says this in this synagogue, he takes the scroll,

10:29.826 --> 10:36.355
He rolls it up and he sits down, and he says to all the people who are listening, who are very familiar with his passage.

10:36.375 --> 10:42.684
He says, today this scripture is fulfilled in your hearing.

10:44.266 --> 10:49.314
And everyone was like, whoa, he's saying, he's the Messiah.

10:50.095 --> 10:51.597
And what is the Messiah going to do?

10:51.637 --> 10:55.282
Not just worship God and teach people to worship God, but let

10:55.458 --> 10:59.683
Justice roll like a river, let righteousness flow like a never-ending stream.

10:59.703 --> 11:06.050
He's going to bind the broken heart if we're claiming freedom for the captives and a release from darkness for the prisoner.

11:07.111 --> 11:10.094
And so Jesus introduces this idea.

11:10.154 --> 11:14.840
He embodies the beautiful righteousness and justice of God.

11:15.901 --> 11:18.043
And he has some difficult conversations.

11:18.163 --> 11:24.050
Often we think of nice Jesus, kind Jesus, gentle Jesus, and he was all those things.

11:24.386 --> 11:27.870
But Jesus had a particular tone for a particular group of people.

11:29.612 --> 11:30.854
And sometimes we get this wrong.

11:31.575 --> 11:42.128
You see, a lot of times you'll hear in church today, those sinful people, those sexually immoral people, those greedy, unrighteous people, we should get mad at them.

11:42.608 --> 11:50.097
But it's interesting that for the most sinful people in Jesus' life, he was gentle and kind and inviting.

11:50.438 --> 11:53.842
He called them to repentance, but Jesus got angry

11:54.690 --> 12:08.786
at the people who sang the loudest, who knew the Scriptures the best, and you wore a mask of superiority that they were better somehow than other people.

12:09.954 --> 12:20.107
He threw over tables in the temple and he dedicated an entire chapter, an entire sermon, Matthew chapter 23, toward that type of spiritual superiority.

12:20.527 --> 12:27.215
I'm better than you and you and those people because I know all the words to the song, I know how to pray, I know how to fast, I give.

12:27.275 --> 12:31.861
And Jesus says this in Matthew 23 to people like that.

12:32.061 --> 12:35.926
It sounds a lot like the prophet Amos and the prophet Isaiah.

12:37.007 --> 12:39.090
Matthew 23, 23, woe to you.

12:39.714 --> 12:43.839
Teachers of the law and Pharisees, you hypocrites.

12:45.161 --> 12:50.047
You give a tenth of your spices, a mint, and dill, and cumin.

12:51.068 --> 12:57.496
But you have neglected the more important matters of the law, justice, mercy, and faithfulness.

12:58.157 --> 13:02.062
You should have practiced the latter without neglecting the former.

13:03.524 --> 13:08.530
And he goes on to say, you swallow, you strain out a mat, and you swallow a camel.

13:09.058 --> 13:12.522
And you'll go across the earth to make people twice the son of hell that you are.

13:12.542 --> 13:21.173
I mean, Jesus did not hold back to people who felt superior because of the way they sang or fasted or gave or prayed.

13:21.834 --> 13:26.619
And he's like, guys, guys, guys, guys, guys, you're doing all the right, you found all the rules, but you're missing the point.

13:27.781 --> 13:30.184
You're not exercising justice.

13:30.204 --> 13:31.165
You're not showing mercy.

13:31.185 --> 13:34.089
There's no kindness or faithfulness in you.

13:34.109 --> 13:36.191
You can't have it this way and that way.

13:36.211 --> 13:38.514
The vertical and the horizontal,

13:39.266 --> 13:39.707
to match.

13:40.788 --> 13:46.635
And so we look at the early church, the people who follow Jesus, and we see them following this pattern.

13:46.655 --> 13:48.978
James, the brother of Jesus, would write to the early church.

13:48.998 --> 13:51.401
He would say, you know, you want to live a life of pure religion?

13:51.421 --> 13:52.863
Do what?

13:52.963 --> 13:57.368
Care for the widow and the orphan in their distress and keep herself unspotted from the world.

13:58.370 --> 14:03.836
You want to look at the early church's record of not just preaching the gospel and singing songs of worship and holding prayer.

14:03.856 --> 14:08.402
He's been going into the street collecting for widows who are hungry,

14:08.834 --> 14:14.281
Helping people affected by famine, caring for the sick and the poor and the needy.

14:14.301 --> 14:15.923
This is the entire book of Acts.

14:15.963 --> 14:17.565
It's not just the preaching of the gospel.

14:17.585 --> 14:19.207
It's the demonstration of the gospel.

14:20.169 --> 14:22.171
And we see this over and over.

14:22.191 --> 14:25.255
And so just a simple point.

14:26.317 --> 14:29.701
Loving the vulnerable is our spiritual heritage.

14:29.721 --> 14:30.762
And I want to take a moment.

14:30.782 --> 14:36.690
I want to think about the spiritual heritage we've been given that for generations, Christians haven't just

14:36.866 --> 14:39.490
sang songs of worship and prayed prayers and taught God's word.

14:40.372 --> 14:44.378
But they've demonstrated what justice and mercy look like in a community.

14:44.418 --> 14:47.082
And there's a blessing for this.

14:47.342 --> 14:53.572
We go back to Isaiah 58 and look what God says to the people who live in this way, what God's desire is for his people.

14:54.454 --> 14:59.782
If we will lose the chains of injustice and set the oppressed free and share our food, what will happen?

15:00.103 --> 15:00.603
Verse eight.

15:01.965 --> 15:04.850
Then your light will break forth like the dawn.

15:05.378 --> 15:11.644
and your healing will quickly appear, and your righteousness will go before you, and the glory of the Lord will be your rear guard.

15:12.605 --> 15:14.166
Then you will call, and the Lord will answer.

15:14.226 --> 15:16.989
You'll cry for help, and he will say, here I am.

15:17.009 --> 15:32.243
And if you do away with the yoke of oppression, with the pointing finger, and the malicious talk, and if you spend yourselves in behalf of the hungry, and satisfy the needs of the oppressed, then your light will rise, and the darkness, and your night will become like the noonday.

15:33.364 --> 15:35.346
And the Lord will guide you always.

15:35.938 --> 15:40.002
And he will satisfy your needs in his son's scorched land and will strengthen your frame.

15:40.062 --> 15:47.230
And you will be like a well-watered garden, like a spring whose waters never fail.

15:47.250 --> 15:52.455
And your people will rebuild the ancient ruins and raise up the age-old foundations.

15:52.495 --> 16:00.103
You will be called the repair of broken walls, the restorer of streets with dwellings.

16:00.123 --> 16:02.546
What is God saying to his people?

16:02.658 --> 16:10.947
The vertical and the horizontal the half to match, the commandment, the greatest commandment to love God with all your heart, soul, mind, and strength and to love your neighbor as yourself.

16:10.967 --> 16:13.991
You can't disconnect those two things.

16:14.071 --> 16:20.659
And if you, my people, live in this way, your light will shine in the darkness like the noon day sun.

16:20.899 --> 16:26.906
You'll be satisfied in the quiet place with the well of God's provision and grace and generosity.

16:26.926 --> 16:30.770
And you will develop a reputation as a certain group of people

16:31.490 --> 16:35.356
who are the restorer of things that are broken.

16:36.678 --> 16:57.830
Imagine the people of God known for taking broken things and laboring in the mess in the brokenness to repair them and the people go, wow, you know, wherever Christians go, things that are broken become whole, people that are sick become healed, people that are lost are found, people in darkness become light.

16:58.170 --> 17:00.754
This is our spiritual heritage.

17:01.314 --> 17:06.002
and we want to be the people who take this heritage and run with it for the next generation.

17:06.102 --> 17:07.004
Is anybody with me today?

17:08.126 --> 17:14.637
This is Isaiah speaking for God, giving this vision for what God's people are called to do.

17:15.919 --> 17:17.502
Let's talk about our spiritual history.

17:17.522 --> 17:26.898
Listen, the church has always been at its best when we've been living this out and we've always been at our worst when we haven't.

17:27.362 --> 17:29.104
And so I wanna go through history.

17:29.124 --> 17:37.837
We're just gonna go through a little history lesson and just see how we've gotten to today and maybe some of the ways that Christians have lived out this type of life.

17:38.017 --> 17:46.068
And many of these quotations, many of these ideas came from religious opponents of Christianity, people who tried to stop Christianity from growing.

17:46.088 --> 17:49.072
So after we get through the book of Acts, well, what happened?

17:49.092 --> 17:49.974
Well, history tells us.

17:50.635 --> 17:55.922
Well, in 112 AD, there was a man named Cleany the Younger and he interrogated Christians.

17:56.290 --> 18:03.057
because he wanted to suppress what he called this contagious superstition that is Christianity.

18:03.958 --> 18:12.027
And he was shocked at how Christians supported other Christians, how there was this network of support that they would always help and serve each other.

18:12.087 --> 18:23.199
And during the two major plagues of the first and second century in Rome, as people were dying of the plagues, Christians stayed in the cities while people fled for their lives.

18:24.581 --> 18:25.842
And they cared for the poor.

18:26.562 --> 18:27.664
and they cared for the sick.

18:28.205 --> 18:54.386
Christians actually moved into places of danger to care for people, and because of this, now all of a sudden, not because they're trying to seize political power, but they became the mayors and the leaders, and what became a persecuted group of Christians eventually became the official religion of the Roman Empire, not through conquest, not through power, but through humble service, providing justice, letting it roll like a river,

18:55.010 --> 19:04.263
and Dionysus of Alexander in 260 AD described the heart of Christians who had walked toward danger, and even were willing to sacrifice their lives to serve people who were sick.

19:05.986 --> 19:18.584
He wrote, most of our brothers showed unbounded love and loyalty, never sparing themselves, tending to the sick, ministering to them in Christ, and with them departed this life, serenely happy.

19:20.367 --> 19:22.610
It's as if they believe the words of Jesus.

19:23.618 --> 19:27.463
that when he said in Matthew 25, whatever you did for the least of these, my brothers, you did to me.

19:28.605 --> 19:29.986
When I was hungry, you fed me.

19:30.827 --> 19:32.990
When I was in prison, you visited me.

19:33.050 --> 19:34.472
When I was naked, you clothed me.

19:35.153 --> 19:39.319
And whatever you do to the least of these you did to me, these Christians, they believe that so deeply.

19:39.339 --> 19:41.642
They were willing to lay down their lives to care for sick people.

19:41.662 --> 19:43.444
They didn't even know.

19:43.604 --> 19:47.529
And the opponents of Christianity, this is a contagious, superstitious thing.

19:47.570 --> 19:50.994
We got to figure out how to stop it, but they couldn't stop it.

19:52.290 --> 20:03.963
And so one of the other ways that Christians distinguish themselves and let justice and righteousness flow like a river and never any stream was their treatment of unwanted children.

20:05.284 --> 20:10.370
So there was a practice in the Roman Empire in the first and the second and the third century.

20:10.390 --> 20:11.531
It was called exposure.

20:12.352 --> 20:21.202
If you had a child that you did not want, and typically this child was a female because male boys, they were, they were wanted, they were more valuable or children with disabilities,

20:21.922 --> 20:29.875
Well, there was a very common practice of taking this baby and laying it on a wall of exposure and letting the elements or the animals do their work.

20:30.215 --> 20:33.060
And these babies would die, just abandoned.

20:34.221 --> 20:37.707
But Christians were like, yeah, that can't happen.

20:37.787 --> 20:40.051
And listen, listen, this was a completely accepted practice.

20:40.071 --> 20:49.746
It sounds so barbaric, but at the height of Greek and Roman ethics, we think of Socrates and Plato and Aristotle, like this idea of Greek virtue is so high, but listen to Aristotle.

20:50.594 --> 20:53.159
Let there be a law that no deformed child should be reared.

20:55.304 --> 21:01.858
If you have a defect of any kind, you're a burden on society you don't deserve to live.

21:02.820 --> 21:11.218
And Christians were like, oh no, because they deeply believed in this idea of the amago day that every child born unborn

21:11.362 --> 21:13.725
You're young, you're old, you're sick, you're healthy.

21:13.745 --> 21:16.028
You're the model of perfection or you're ailing.

21:16.429 --> 21:26.281
Whatever condition you are, every single human being is made in the very image and likeness of God and is worthy of dignity and protection, right?

21:26.301 --> 21:27.283
That's a Christian idea.

21:29.706 --> 21:35.954
And so there was a man in the Calistus and he organized what we're called these

21:36.130 --> 21:43.562
Life watches, that people would, Christians would go hang out at these walls of exposure where babies were left for infanticide and they would take these kids.

21:44.463 --> 21:47.948
And they would raise them as they were their own sons and daughters.

21:47.988 --> 21:56.422
And the idea of adoption that took place in the Roman Empire was fueled by Christians who were caring for abandoned babies.

21:57.163 --> 21:59.446
And this, this is our heritage.

22:00.207 --> 22:00.889
This is our legacy.

22:00.909 --> 22:04.434
This led to the foundation of orphanages all across

22:04.610 --> 22:11.120
This region in the second, in the third century, the idea of an orphanage where an abandoned child could be cared for in love is a Christian idea.

22:11.140 --> 22:15.967
It didn't matter what race you were, what language you spoke.

22:16.007 --> 22:17.189
It didn't matter where you came from.

22:17.249 --> 22:19.733
It didn't matter what model of beauty perfection you were.

22:19.753 --> 22:25.701
You were cared for because Christians believed in the dignity of every human being.

22:26.603 --> 22:29.287
And there was a man named Basel.

22:30.008 --> 22:34.194
He was the Christian Bisser ancestry in the fourth century.

22:34.786 --> 22:44.115
And he came up with this idea that we need to create a care center for people, not just for orphans, but for the elderly, a place of hospice, a place of care.

22:44.135 --> 22:49.079
We need to create a hospital because back in the day, if you were sick, you couldn't afford a doctor.

22:49.139 --> 22:59.069
Only rich people had doctors back in the day is like, what if we provided doctors to care for anyone who walked in at no cost to themselves because we're Christians and we care.

22:59.129 --> 23:04.594
He built this massive, massive facility that cared for, again, those who were orphans.

23:04.802 --> 23:06.244
And those who were sick.

23:06.264 --> 23:08.207
I mean, think about the word hospital.

23:09.409 --> 23:19.985
Hospital comes from the word hospitality, the Greek word, the love, fileo of strangers.

23:21.708 --> 23:28.338
The first hospital, the first public hospital in world history was started by Christians to say,

23:28.418 --> 23:38.593
No matter who is sick, no matter who is dying, no matter who has a family or not, we're gonna care for them in Jesus' name because he commanded us to live in this way.

23:40.997 --> 23:45.824
And not just children, but even in death.

23:47.928 --> 23:54.738
Christians were the first people that had this idea that if you died, you needed

23:54.850 --> 23:59.900
a dignified burial, whether you were slave or free or rich or poor.

24:00.160 --> 24:02.585
If you go to Rome today, you see these things called catacombs.

24:03.266 --> 24:04.969
My wife and I have been through many of these catacombs.

24:05.270 --> 24:12.363
These catacombs were burial places and Christians were the first people that didn't matter what class you were or what family were from.

24:12.704 --> 24:13.906
You have slaves.

24:14.178 --> 24:17.361
that are buried next to noble people in all these different catacombs.

24:17.401 --> 24:22.367
And it was the Christian way to say, if you're made in the image of God, even in death, you deserve dignity.

24:22.387 --> 24:27.392
And we're gonna take care of you and bury you in honor because this is what God did for us.

24:27.452 --> 24:29.575
This is a Christian idea, right?

24:31.156 --> 24:36.903
Let justice roll like a river and a righteousness like a never ending stream.

24:37.503 --> 24:40.146
And again, the religious opponents of Christianity,

24:40.674 --> 24:44.778
did not like this because it took away their power and their influence over people.

24:44.818 --> 24:48.522
There's a man named Julian, the apostate.

24:48.542 --> 24:50.423
He was hostile to Christians in Christianity.

24:50.443 --> 24:53.406
And he complained to all of his people in letters that we have today.

24:53.446 --> 24:55.388
And here's one of the lines of one of the letters.

24:56.730 --> 24:59.692
He says, the impious Galileans, those are the Christians.

25:00.633 --> 25:04.537
They not only take care of their own poor, but ours as well.

25:05.438 --> 25:07.981
And everyone can see that our people lack aid from us.

25:08.921 --> 25:09.522
I love this.

25:10.146 --> 25:11.428
He's like, we're bad leaders.

25:11.488 --> 25:11.848
We know it.

25:11.868 --> 25:15.674
We don't care about people, but they're making us look bad because now they take care of their people.

25:16.114 --> 25:17.276
They're taking care of our people.

25:17.977 --> 25:20.660
And if this keeps up, we're going to lose our power.

25:21.762 --> 25:23.444
And so he's writing to all these people.

25:23.484 --> 25:25.467
Let's imitate the Christians.

25:25.507 --> 25:29.593
We need to consolidate our power because we're losing to all these people.

25:29.613 --> 25:34.419
They're caring for people that aren't even their own with love and justice and compassion and mercy.

25:34.459 --> 25:37.764
And you can see the frustration in this letter.

25:38.565 --> 25:39.506
And this, again,

25:39.810 --> 25:42.413
is the heritage that Christians have now.

25:43.054 --> 25:46.297
Now, most of these stories and most of this part of history, maybe you're not familiar with.

25:46.698 --> 25:48.139
I'm gonna fast forward a thousand years.

25:48.159 --> 25:56.408
And there's a lot that happened over those thousand years, but I'm gonna take you to the 1800s to a man and his wife, William and Catherine Booth.

25:56.428 --> 25:58.731
They formed an organization called the Salvation Army.

25:58.751 --> 26:00.313
Anybody ever heard of the Salvation Army, right?

26:00.873 --> 26:01.794
And here was the idea.

26:01.834 --> 26:08.722
We're gonna go out of our church walls and we're gonna have a revival meeting right in front

26:09.186 --> 26:09.787
of the bar.

26:12.572 --> 26:12.672
Yeah.

26:12.692 --> 26:18.321
And we're going to play worship songs and we're going to invite drunk people who are bound by alcoholism.

26:19.082 --> 26:24.331
And we're going to invite them into a relationship with Jesus and then we're going to put them in homes and halfway houses and care for them and love them.

26:24.351 --> 26:33.045
And not only that, we're going to help with orphanages and we're going to help lobby and advocate for women and children who are vulnerable.

26:33.065 --> 26:36.210
See, this is the start of the industrial revolution in England.

26:36.962 --> 26:40.346
And well, there were no laws to protect children that worked in factories.

26:40.366 --> 26:48.815
In fact, half of the people that worked in factories in England at this time were children, working 12 to 16 hour days in very dangerous situations.

26:48.855 --> 26:53.380
It was not uncommon for children to be killed or maimed in their everyday work because they were smaller.

26:53.400 --> 26:58.085
They could work in these small shafts in the coal mines and they could reach behind equipment that was already running.

26:58.225 --> 27:01.508
If they lost a hand or they lost their life, let's get another kid.

27:01.548 --> 27:03.250
And if you were an orphan and had to a family,

27:03.874 --> 27:07.399
There was no one to advocate for you and William Booth and Catherine Booth said, there's no way.

27:07.920 --> 27:15.451
This is right that people who call themselves Christians are maximizing profit in their business and not caring for these women and children who have no rights.

27:15.491 --> 27:31.634
And so they lobbied not just to work for the abolition of slavery, but for women's rights and children's rights because they believed in this crazy idea that every man, woman and child is made in the very image and likeness of God.

27:32.834 --> 27:37.501
worth fighting for, worth defending, because God did that for us.

27:38.482 --> 27:40.806
This is our spiritual heritage.

27:42.128 --> 27:43.730
So it's not just William and Catherine Booth.

27:44.772 --> 27:49.559
Let you go across to America, and there's a man named Charles Lorraine Brace.

27:50.640 --> 27:53.424
And he started something called the orphan train.

27:53.445 --> 28:01.536
You see, in the East, in New York, in Boston, in Philadelphia, there were tens of thousands, hundreds of thousands of abandoned children.

28:01.557 --> 28:02.578
They're all in the streets.

28:03.394 --> 28:06.179
being used in child prostitution, being used in child labor.

28:06.199 --> 28:07.101
And he said, this is wrong.

28:07.121 --> 28:07.782
We need you to something.

28:07.802 --> 28:10.246
He organized this train that would go across America.

28:10.967 --> 28:13.712
And at every stop, families could take in children and adopt them.

28:14.053 --> 28:26.034
And this idea was so innovative at the time, it helped save thousands of lives and gives 200,000 children found families because of a man who said, I'm not just going to sing my song in my church.

28:26.946 --> 28:34.795
I'm gonna fight for justice and a righteous in my city, in my nation, because this is what God did for me, and I have a chance to do it for someone else, right?

28:36.597 --> 28:48.850
You see, the church has always been at her best when she has advocated for the poor and for the vulnerable.

28:48.870 --> 28:56.338
Where the songs that we have sung in church and the stories we have read about who God is are reflected

28:56.770 --> 28:59.854
in our everyday life, but you know, there's a dark side to Christian history.

29:01.435 --> 29:03.057
If we're just being honest, it's not all good.

29:04.659 --> 29:24.242
You see, when Christians gravitate toward power at any cost, influence a chance to make money, to accumulate cultural power, well, we see things like the crusades,

29:26.722 --> 29:33.191
The inquisitions, the opposition of civil rights and abolition.

29:34.032 --> 29:49.675
And every once in a while in Christian history, God raises up another prophet like an Amos, like an Isaiah, not to tell the future, but to talk in a very scathing critique about how Christians have disconnected their worship from their life.

29:49.775 --> 29:54.962
And one of those men in American history was a man named Frederick

29:55.330 --> 29:55.710
Douglas.

29:55.730 --> 29:56.711
He was born as a slave.

29:58.093 --> 29:59.735
As a young man, he became a Christian.

30:01.136 --> 30:03.599
He began to read the Bible and pour over its pages.

30:03.739 --> 30:09.665
He had experienced things that were so hard for his brain to connect with Christianity.

30:09.725 --> 30:17.254
I grew up in this place where I would watch a pastor pray before he whipped his slave.

30:19.396 --> 30:21.458
I watched a pastor preach a sermon about

30:21.858 --> 30:27.566
the sanctity of marriage and family, and then auction off a family and separate them that afternoon.

30:29.088 --> 30:36.618
I watched him talk about sexual purity, and I watched all this sexual immorality with people who were seeing this property, not even as human.

30:37.960 --> 30:46.371
There was this disconnect between the songs they were singing, and the Bible they were reading, and the way they were living.

30:47.853 --> 30:51.538
He wrote in this

30:52.386 --> 30:56.271
a very direct prophetic way, and this is one of those things that he wrote.

30:57.813 --> 31:04.542
Between the Christianity of this land and the Christianity of Christ, I recognize the widest possible difference.

31:04.563 --> 31:11.832
So why that to receive the one as good and pure and holy is of necessity to reject the other as bad, corrupt, and wicked?

31:13.114 --> 31:17.120
To be the friend of the one is of necessity to be the enemy of the other.

31:18.622 --> 31:21.906
I love the pure, peaceful, and impartial Christianity of Christ,

31:22.050 --> 31:31.424
But I therefore hate the corrupt slave-holding, women whipping, cradle plundering, partial and hypocritical Christianity of this land.

31:33.347 --> 31:45.166
And it was men like Frederick Douglass and people who learned to use their voice that pointed out some of the hypocrisy of people who would sing their songs and read their Bible and have a complete disconnection from how they treated other people.

31:47.149 --> 31:48.350
The church is always at her best.

31:49.652 --> 31:50.674
We in our vertical worship.

31:51.298 --> 31:53.622
translates to our horizontal compassion for people.

31:53.642 --> 32:02.876
When we see the image of God in anyone born or unborn, young or old, sick or healthy, this is the call of every Christian to love people in Jesus' name.

32:02.996 --> 32:03.577
Anybody with me?

32:03.837 --> 32:04.739
This is our heritage.

32:06.962 --> 32:10.567
And there are always those moments of history where you like scratch your head.

32:10.608 --> 32:17.458
Like there are many narratives of German Christians who would hear the rail cars go by their church filled with

32:17.666 --> 32:23.775
Jewish men, women, and children on their way to concentration camps and the sound of their cries were so hard to hear.

32:23.815 --> 32:25.077
They just sang louder.

32:26.219 --> 32:27.561
I'm just going to sing louder.

32:27.621 --> 32:29.885
I don't want to hear what's happening outside of here.

32:30.646 --> 32:33.150
I just want to focus on heaven.

32:33.170 --> 32:34.211
And God says, I hate that.

32:35.173 --> 32:38.318
And you know, it's so easy for us to look back on Christian history and go, thank God.

32:38.378 --> 32:39.379
I wasn't in the German church.

32:40.241 --> 32:40.801
Thank God.

32:41.322 --> 32:42.644
Because I would have done it differently.

32:42.744 --> 32:45.489
Would you have?

32:45.529 --> 32:45.809
See, C.S.

32:45.849 --> 32:46.450
Lewis.

32:46.882 --> 32:56.295
He says, every generation has what you call cultural snobbery, which is a great way to say it's so easy for us to look back on all these generations.

32:56.335 --> 32:57.296
God, I can't believe they did that.

32:58.117 --> 32:59.599
I can't believe they believe that.

33:00.521 --> 33:03.505
I can't believe they preached that or wrote that or said that.

33:03.845 --> 33:05.548
What was wrong with those people?

33:06.929 --> 33:07.290
And C.S.

33:07.310 --> 33:09.553
Lewis says, you know, they're going to write about you.

33:11.596 --> 33:16.082
Like if Jesus doesn't come back two or three generations from now, what will

33:16.162 --> 33:20.728
Christians say about this Christian group here in the 2020s.

33:20.789 --> 33:27.278
Now, if we don't think they will, that's cultural snobbery.

33:28.419 --> 33:30.002
The question is, what will they say?

33:31.163 --> 33:32.405
What is our blind spot?

33:33.386 --> 33:40.056
If we're called to love like Jesus, then where are there gaps in our compassion, the way that we live?

33:40.076 --> 33:41.618
And this is important to think about

33:42.530 --> 33:43.772
This isn't just a history lesson.

33:43.812 --> 33:47.197
The Bible is like a mirror for us to look and see ourselves.

33:48.800 --> 34:00.097
And so maybe, maybe it's that we are the most affluent generation that has ever existed on planet Earth in the history of the world.

34:01.539 --> 34:11.154
And somehow, with all of that resource, we still keep it to ourselves because somehow we don't feel wealthy.

34:12.898 --> 34:22.667
Maybe it's because we live in a current culture that dehumanizes other people that were able to look at people, those people.

34:22.767 --> 34:31.556
And you fill in the blank, we talked about it last week, those people, those people I should fear, those people I should hate.

34:32.357 --> 34:39.423
And there's plenty of partisan hacks who are gonna tell us that, that are gonna demand our allegiance, but our allegiance is not to them.

34:40.865 --> 34:42.226
Our allegiance is to God's word.

34:42.754 --> 34:47.480
It's the way the church has always been at her best.

34:48.741 --> 34:50.283
Don't give in to lesser allegiances.

34:51.745 --> 35:00.396
Don't give in to the hate and the fear-mongering that allows people to accumulate money or power or control.

35:02.038 --> 35:03.279
That's when the church gets lost.

35:04.601 --> 35:05.522
Maybe it's not

35:06.466 --> 35:08.749
that we're the wealthiest generation and we're not sharing.

35:08.950 --> 35:12.034
Maybe it's not that we've dehumanized entire groups of people.

35:12.054 --> 35:27.217
Maybe it's that we have compassion fatigue, that there's so many problems and needs as a hurricane here and a famine there and injustice here and a war and like there's so much stuff and we're just like, I mean, I can't even do a shoebox to be honest because I'm just overwhelmed.

35:27.277 --> 35:28.879
I'm exhausted.

35:30.281 --> 35:36.370
And we don't do anything at all because we're so with everything.

35:37.570 --> 35:49.502
Now, I don't know what it's gonna be, but I pray that God would use his word like a mirror to show us ourselves so that we could live in a way that loves like Jesus.

35:50.823 --> 35:57.950
Now, if you think that we're the only ones that have had this problem, no, I mean, Jonathan Edwards, he taught a sermon in 1733.

35:57.990 --> 36:02.675
And here's the title of the sermon that Jonathan Edwards preached.

36:02.695 --> 36:05.778
It was called The Duty of Charity for the Poor.

36:06.850 --> 36:12.756
And he talked about in 1733, the three reasons why Christians don't help people.

36:14.878 --> 36:16.099
Here's the first reason.

36:16.539 --> 36:18.521
He says Christians don't help people.

36:19.542 --> 36:21.804
They're in need, but they're not desperate.

36:23.526 --> 36:27.389
So we might say, well, they have no food, but they have a cell phone, so they should figure it out.

36:27.770 --> 36:28.671
They're not desperate, desperate.

36:28.691 --> 36:29.571
They're not starving to death.

36:30.632 --> 36:35.897
And so because they're not starving to death, I want to help someone who's like right there on death door.

36:35.997 --> 36:36.658
I'll help them.

36:37.986 --> 36:40.169
But those people don't seem so desperate, so I'm not gonna help them.

36:40.189 --> 36:40.830
1733.

36:42.052 --> 36:47.159
Second thing you said, why Christians don't help their neighbors or friends, I don't have much to spare.

36:48.742 --> 36:50.404
They're not desperate and I don't have a lot either.

36:50.444 --> 36:56.733
And what Jonathan ever said, what you really meant to say is I can't help you without it costing me something.

36:58.716 --> 37:02.201
And so because it cost me something, yeah, you're not desperate.

37:02.942 --> 37:05.426
I'm not really ready to help you where it hurts me.

37:06.754 --> 37:08.677
And then the third one, remember, this is 1733.

37:09.638 --> 37:10.359
The third one is this.

37:11.921 --> 37:12.883
They brought this on themselves.

37:14.986 --> 37:16.187
Yeah, that's why I'm not going to help them.

37:17.710 --> 37:20.053
And those people, they did this to themselves.

37:20.073 --> 37:21.094
That's why they don't have any money.

37:22.196 --> 37:29.666
That's why they're in this desperate space of, I mean, I'm not going to help someone like that because they did this to themselves.

37:29.686 --> 37:32.210
1733, sound very familiar.

37:33.602 --> 37:35.204
Yeah, this is the human condition.

37:35.224 --> 37:36.746
It has nothing to do with our cultural moment.

37:36.766 --> 37:38.788
It has to do with our own defense mechanism.

37:38.828 --> 37:39.449
See, here's the deal.

37:40.230 --> 37:41.011
You know who I wanna help?

37:41.932 --> 37:46.257
I wanna help someone who's in a circumstance that's no fault of their own.

37:46.277 --> 37:48.300
They haven't done anything wrong.

37:48.320 --> 37:51.624
And that when I help them, they experience this deep sense of gratitude.

37:51.644 --> 37:54.627
Like, thank you so much, Doug, for what you've done for me.

37:54.888 --> 37:58.532
And I'm gonna take what you've done for me and I'm gonna help other people and they give me a hug.

37:58.792 --> 38:00.234
God bless you, you're like Jesus.

38:01.856 --> 38:03.378
You know something about those people?

38:03.682 --> 38:04.443
They don't exist.

38:06.486 --> 38:07.468
All right, let's just be honest.

38:08.289 --> 38:18.544
The people who've never done anything wrong that are helpless victims to all these circumstances and are gonna say thank you and take what you've given them and make the most of it, I don't know if I've ever met a person like that in my whole life.

38:20.226 --> 38:21.148
And isn't that the point?

38:22.690 --> 38:23.612
When did Jesus help you?

38:26.396 --> 38:31.764
You see, I wanna say this, guilt is not gonna motivate us to help people.

38:31.804 --> 38:33.426
This is not a sermon about guilt.

38:34.850 --> 38:35.911
as guilt doesn't work.

38:37.493 --> 38:48.727
Only thing that helps awaken a Christian whose heart is not burning with compassion for people around him or her is grace.

38:50.008 --> 38:52.671
A heart awakened to the gospel for what Jesus did for you.

38:54.974 --> 38:55.935
Love to people.

38:57.798 --> 38:58.478
Love people.

39:00.321 --> 39:04.786
In every Christian that has an experience or

39:05.026 --> 39:08.830
shared compassion with others that part of their heart is asleep and needs to be awakened.

39:08.850 --> 39:17.178
And there's a direct relationship between how much a person understands how much grace they have received and experienced from God to how they will show it to other people.

39:18.860 --> 39:26.728
And this is an act of grace to realize I didn't deserve it and Jesus came from me and it cost him way more than it cost me to help this person.

39:26.768 --> 39:30.132
And there were so many times I never told Jesus, thank you.

39:30.152 --> 39:32.434
And he didn't stop blessing me.

39:33.122 --> 39:35.526
He didn't stop healing me, didn't stop redeeming my life.

39:35.606 --> 39:41.034
And so wow, when I think about what he did for me, I want to do this for other people.

39:41.975 --> 39:43.417
I mean, Jesus talked about this, right?

39:44.719 --> 39:47.924
He said things like, Jesus said crazy stuff.

39:48.845 --> 39:51.008
Like don't just love your friends, but love your enemies.

39:51.930 --> 39:53.072
And you know why you should love them?

39:54.173 --> 39:59.100
Because you should be like my father who is kind to the wicked and the ungrateful.

40:00.783 --> 40:02.866
Wait, why should you be kind to wicked people?

40:03.938 --> 40:06.561
in ungrateful people, because God is.

40:07.662 --> 40:08.363
And he's your father.

40:09.104 --> 40:13.850
And you've gone from sinner to saint, from enemy of God to child of God, and he says, so be like your father.

40:14.390 --> 40:15.412
This is not a book of rules.

40:16.653 --> 40:18.435
Do a shoebox and help a kid or else.

40:20.718 --> 40:20.778
No.

40:20.798 --> 40:23.341
Fill up a grocery bag and deliver it, or you're a bad Christian.

40:23.361 --> 40:25.263
No, no, no, this is not a book of rules.

40:26.825 --> 40:30.770
This is just an awakening of a heart to say for all that he has done for you.

40:32.098 --> 40:34.261
What could you begin to do for someone else, right?

40:35.122 --> 40:39.487
And it doesn't happen in the day and it doesn't happen because of one sermon and I just want to encourage you.

40:39.507 --> 40:42.351
And it doesn't happen by you leaving here and doing a thousand things.

40:43.612 --> 40:48.919
Maybe you just begin to think, God, what area of injustice in our world grieves my heart?

40:50.961 --> 40:53.724
What area do I see the need for compassion?

40:53.744 --> 40:54.686
I think about it all the time.

40:54.706 --> 40:56.207
I just haven't done anything yet.

40:57.449 --> 41:01.554
And as you meditate, like how do I advocate for unborn children?

41:02.114 --> 41:04.356
so that they could be born and thrive and have good families.

